In a BadUSB attack, the malicious payload is delivered via an attack vector that disguises itself as a Human Interface Device (HID), typically a keyboard. In this paper, we propose NoBU, a novel, efficient, and effective solution to counter this threat that leverages information contextual to the physical space surrounding the targeted asset. NoBU captures vibrations from keystrokes and correlates them with input signals to distinguish between legitimate, human-generated inputs, and fake ones—blocking the latter. We evaluated our solution across various environments and keyboard types, demonstrating NoBU’s promising capabilities. A preliminary version of NoBU, which constitutes the core of our proposal, achieves an accuracy of 99.92%, scoring 99.83% on precision and a recall of 100% in identifying malicious keystrokes; hence, the system does not accept false negatives. We further enhanced our detection methodology, moving from continuous input validation to seamless keyboard enrollment, still leveraging the basic idea introduced by NoBU. The new proposal (eNoBU), achieves a staggering accuracy of 100%, while improving the user experience and further reducing the system overhead. These results suggest that eNoBU, leveraging the cyber-physical properties that naturally arise from human-computer interactions, is a potential candidate for a definitive solution to the BadUSB threat.